So what was the big deal with him pick pocketing before sapping?  As
long as hes not getting caught then let him do his thing I say.
Unless he was taking the time to pick pocket every single mob in a
pull before sapping, then hes just severely slowing down the group.
And as for trying to solo mobs in an instance, you shoud have just
booted him and replaced him instead of quitting the group.  Unless of
course, he was the group leader, then you're screwed.

I like when the tank moves, but he definantly should have waited and
let people who needed mana catch up.  I've been in groups where the
tank would not move on to the next pull unless everyone was at full
health and mana.  And I mean every pull.  As a warlock, I don't drink
often.  If I am above 50% I don't even bother unless we are about to
pull a boss.  As a result, I don't carry around much water.  I buy a
stack and it lasts me for weeks.  But this warrior would just not move
until I had mana.  Dark pact FTW.  I tanked WC with my druid this past
weekend.  First time tanking for a group.  Only 1 death at the very
end.  WC really isn't all that hard though.  But after every pull I
looked at health and mana bars, waited to see if anyone stopped to
drink, then moved on.  We steamrolled that instance.

I don't like quitting groups.  I prefer to replace people holding the
group back.  I almost quit 1 group because of another warlock in the
group that didn't understand the concept of seduce a target but don't
attack it or seduce will break.  He spent half the instance dotting
the target I was seducing, and the other half dotting the target he
was supposed to seduce.  We had a tank who spent the whole time
whining that there was no CC because the warlocks sucked, nevermind
the fact that I spent all my time trying to reapply the seduce broken
by his paladin AoE or the other warlocks dots.
